      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Your article about wind power, ''Is the Answer Blowing in the Wind?'' (Nov. 5), gave an excellent overview of current efforts to tap into this clean, abundant and domestic energy source.</p>
        <p>While wind output is inherently variable, it can be successfully integrated into our electric grid. Contrary to findings in the ABS Energy Research report you cited, a U.K. Energy Research Center report and a paper from United States utility associations find that challenges posed by wind as an intermittent power source are manageable with proper planning and operating procedures.</p>
        <p>A recent study commissioned by the New York State Energy Research and Development Authority found that here in New York we could integrate 3,300 megawatts (or 10 percent) of wind power into our grid without any significant reliability problem.</p>
        <p>Wind power alone will not solve our energy problems. But together with other renewable energy technologies, aggressive energy efficiency efforts, and cleaning up our antiquated power plants, wind presents a viable answer.</p>
        <p>Gordian Raacke  Bridgehampton, N.Y.</p>
        <p>The writer is executive director of Renewable Energy Long Island.</p>
      </block>
